]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "The framework defines a full DT lifecycle that starts with device modeling directly in the BIM environment (defining sensors, actuators, controllers), proceeds to model‑driven engineering (MDE) that extracts a structured representation and automatically generates deployable DT artifacts, followed by runtime operation where continuous real‑time data exchange keeps the physical building and its digital counterpart synchronized, and interactive 3‑D visualization enables monitoring and control. The lifecycle is extensible through standardized extension points that allow integration of custom services, supporting ongoing evolution and governance of the twin."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "The framework evaluates the correspondence between the DT and its physical counterpart using the Overall Digital Twin Entanglement (ODTE) metric, which quantifies how well the generated DT reflects the real building. Validation is performed by comparing runtime telemetry (sensor streams, actuator states) against the modeled expectations, enabling detection of deviations. Uncertainty sources such as modeling gaps in BIM are acknowledged, and the ODTE score serves as a quality‑assurance indicator guiding further refinement of models and data pipelines."
]

instance horizontal_integration : DTDFVocab:HoriIntegration [
    base:desc "Interoperability is addressed through non‑functional requirements that demand compatibility with heterogeneous systems. The framework relies on standardized extension points and open interfaces to integrate external services, analytics, and enterprise systems. Specific data exchange protocols are not enumerated, but the design emphasizes modular integration and bidirectional communication with external components."
]

instance standardization : DTDFVocab:Standardization [
    base:desc "The solution is built to be compatible with existing AECO‑specific standards such as BIM, ensuring that device models and control logic are anchored in industry‑accepted building information models. For interoperability and real‑time data exchange, the framework integrates Eclipse Hono and Eclipse Ditto, leveraging their IoT communication and digital twin protocols to connect physical devices with the twin. The architecture also follows a modular, standardized extension‑point model to facilitate compliance with broader interoperability frameworks."
]
